{"cursor":"3848","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist |name = Hugo Schiff |image = |image_size = |caption =\n|birth_date = |birth_place = Frankfurt, Germany |residence = |nationality =\n|death_date = |death_place = Florence, Italy |field = |work_institution =\nUniversity of Pisa, Florence (Museo di Storia Naturale, University of Turin\n|alma_mater = University of GÃ¶ttingen |doctoral_advisor = Friedrich WÃ¶hler\n|doctoral_students = |known_for = Schiff base, Schiff test |prizes =\n|religion = |footnotes = }}'Hugo (Ugo) Schiff' (26 April 1834 – 8\nSeptember 1915) was a German Chemist. This article is largely a translation\nfrom the German Wikipedia article. These references are taken from\nthere. Introduzione allo studio della chimica, series of Schiff's\nlessons at the Museo di Scienze Naturali, Edizioni Loescher, Torino,\n'1876'. EinfÃ¼hrung in das Studium der Chemie, Prof. Hugo Schiff, Ed.\nVerlag von Theobald Grieben, Berlin, '1876'. Untersuchungen Ã¼ber\nMetallhaltige Anilinderivate und Ã¼ber die Bildung des Anilinroths, Hugo Schiff,\nEd. Verlag von J. Springer, Berlin, '1864' Notes from Schiff's lessons\ncompiled by his pupil Andrea Torricelli, Voll. I - II, '1897'. He\ndiscovered Schiff bases and other imines, and was responsible for research into\naldehydes and had the Schiff test named after him. He also worked in the field\nof amino acids and the Biuret reagent.\n\nBorn in Frankfurt am Main, Schiff was a student of Friedrich WÃ¶hler in\nGÃ¶ttingen. He completed his dissertation (Ãber einige Naphthyl- und\nPhenylderivate) also supervised by WÃ¶hler in 1857. In the same year, due to\npolitical turmoil, Schiff left Germany in 1857 for Switzerland and the\nUniversity of Bern. Hugo (Ugo) Schiff, Schiff Bases, and a Century of b-\nLactam Synthesis Thomas T. Tidwell Angew. Chem. Int. Ed. '2007', 46, 2â7 PMID\n18022986 He was a supporter of socialism and reportedly corresponded with\nKarl Marx and Friedrich Engels. He also was a cofounder of the socialist Italian\nnewspaper L'Avanti in 1894.\n\nSchiff moved to Italy in 1863 holding positions in Pisa and then Florence (Museo\ndi Storia Naturale). In 1870 he cofounded the Gazzetta Chimica Italiana together\nwith Stanislao Cannizzaro. In 1877 he became Professor of General Chemistry in\nTurin and returned to Florence in 1879 as Professor of General Chemistry at what\nlater would become the University of Florence where he founded the Chemical\nInstitute of the University of Florence. Schiff died in Florence.\n\nIn the University of Florence the Hugo Schiff International Store House still\nexists today.\n","linknr":144,"url":"Hugo_Schiff","recorded":1363425142,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Hugo_Schiff&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Hugo_Schiff&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/Frankfurt","/wiki/Germany","/wiki/Florence","/wiki/Italy","/wiki/University_of_Pisa","/wiki/Florence","/wiki/University_of_Turin","/wiki/Alma_mater","/wiki/University_of_G%C3%B6ttingen","/wiki/Doctoral_advisor","/wiki/Friedrich_W%C3%B6hler","/wiki/Schiff_base","/wiki/Schiff_test","/wiki/Germany","/wiki/Chemist","#cite_note-1","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-3","#cite_note-4","#cite_note-5